                <html>
                <head>
                    <title>Why You Need To Code Every Day When You’re Learning To Program</title>
                <?php include_once 'Elemental/header.php'; ?><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><br><br><h5> This article is reformatted from originally published at <a href="https://betterprogramming.pub/why-you-need-to-code-every-day-when-youre-learning-to-pro-a4d022e70459"><strong>TDS(Towards Data Science)</strong></a></h5></br><h5> <a href="https://clivethompson.medium.com/?source=post_page-----a4d022e70459--------------------------------">Author : Clive Thompson</a> </h5></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content4 cid-tt5SM2WLsM" id="content4-2" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="row justify-content-center">
                    <div class="title col-md-12 col-lg-9">
                        <h3 class="mbr-section-title mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-2">
                            <strong>Why You Need To Code Every Day When You’re Learning To Program</h3></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5 text-muted">The “Ebbinghaus curve of forgetting” tells us to use it or lose it</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/0*ufnS-Q55L_rQEUOq"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@moritz_photography?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">Moritz Kindler</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">Unsplash</a></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">When I was first teaching myself computer programming, I’d often set aside a big chunk of time on the weekend to work on tutorials. By the end of a couple of hours, I always felt like I’d made real progress.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Alas, by the time the next weekend came around, a lot of what I’d learned would evaporate. “Uh, how do I … select an element in a two-dimensional array, again? I thought I learned this?” <em>Gaaaah halp.</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So I got into a depressing loop: I’d spend the first half of my weekly session just getting back up to speed, re-absorbing the material I’d learned a week ago. It was frustrating.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As you can probably guess by now, this is not the right way to learn to program.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The <em>correct</em> way — as many friends in software told me — is to do a bit of coding every day. Even doing fifteen minutes once a day works better than setting a few hours aside once a week.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Once I started doing that, I found that the concepts truly lodged<em> </em>in my head. Sure, I still forgot things. I still do today; hell, even long-term professional programmers constantly google stuff. But the general <em>gist </em>of coding, the major patterns and concepts, remained present in my mind — so long as I was doing a little every day.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As it turns out, there’s some cool science that explains why a daily routine wins out over a weekly routine.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">It’s called “<mark>The Ebbinghaus Curve of Forgetting</mark>”.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-10">
            <br>
                <hr class="hr5">
            <br>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Back in the 1880s, the German psychologist Hermann Ebbinghaus got interested in the nature of memory — and, more specifically, the nature of forgetting. How long would it take us to forget something we’d just learned?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So he ran an intriguing experiment on himself. He generated 2,300 three-letter combinations. (They were nonsensical, i.e. not real words). Then he sat down to memorize a bunch. He’d also regularly test himself to see whether he could recall a word — and if he couldn’t, how many days it had been since he initially memorized it.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Ebbinghaus discovered that we forget things pretty quickly. Within twenty minutes of first memorizing a bunch of new words, he’d have forgotten about 40 per cent of them. Within an hour, he’d have forgotten a little more than 50 per cent. And when he tested himself a day later, he’d have forgotten even more: About two-thirds of the letter-combinations had now vanished from his memory.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">After that, though, the pace of forgetting slowed down. If he tested himself six days later, the amount he’d forgotten had risen only slightly … to about 75%. In a month, it rose to only roughly 80%.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Basically, he <em>rapidly forgot</em> a majority of the three-letter combinations. But the ones that he had managed to remember? They now seemed to be lodged in his memory, seemingly permanently.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This is what has become known as the <strong>Ebbinghaus Curve of Forgetting</strong>, and you can visualize it this way …</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/0*BYX3eOmdGEqUX-ku.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-10">
            <br>
                <hr class="hr5">
            <br>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Over the years since, cognitive psychologists have generally found that Ebbinghaus’ findings hold up.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Why does forgetting work this way? It’s partly to do with how our short-term memory interacts with our long-term memory.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">When we first encounter a new piece of knowledge, our short-term memory grabs ahold of it — helping us to use that data right here and now while we’re thinking. But short-term memory, as its name implies, doesn’t last terribly long.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Our long-term memory, in contrast, contains the knowledge that really sticks around in our minds. But to get something into your long-term memory, you have to re-encounter that new information frequently. Ideally you have to <em>use</em> that information — you have to use it in a thinking task, or a practical activity.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-10">
            <br>
                <hr class="hr5">
            <br>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">You can see where this is headed, right?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Ebbinghaus and his followers theorized that because we forget things in a predictable fashion, we could hack this process in reverse.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If we actively set ourselves the task of <em>re-encountering the new knowledge</em> every few days, then we’d greatly increase the chance that it’ll pass into our long-term memory — and become part of our mind’s overall knowledge base. It’s “use it or lose it”.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This is precisely what happened to me when I started coding every single day. If I spent a few minutes each day banging away at some programming task — like <a href="https://glitch.com/@community/community-roundup" target="_self">remixing someone’s project on Glitch</a> or <a href="https://codepen.io/spark" target="_self">Codepen</a>, or tinkering with a new library — it kept all the coding concepts I’d learned ready at hand. Plus, learning new things was faster, because I was snapping those new Lego bricks onto ones I’d laid down only days before.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">And of course, this produced wonderful forward momentum! When it became easier to jump into the saddle, I wanted to stay there. I’d sit down intending to do a short burst of coding — then get into a groove, and look up to discover, whoa, I’d spent a couple of hours cranking away (and should have gone to bed long ago, lol).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This is the same thing I’ve noticed with learning new musical techniques. I’m a guitarist, and I do a bit of low-key music production using Logic Pro. If I don’t play (or produce) for a while, I get rusty. If I’m regularly sitting down to play or work on a track, though, everything I’m learning sticks.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">(If you want to get really fancy, by the way, there are apps designed specifically to reverse-hack the Ebbinghaus Curve of Forgetting. They’re called <a href="https://en.softonic.com/top/spaced-repetition-apps" target="_self">“spaced repetition” apps</a>: You create a bunch of flash cards, and then use the app to test yourself every day or so. The software pays attention to what you’ve learned and what you’ve forgotten — and <em>when </em>you’ve learned or forgotten it — so re-quizzes you on material at the precisely right moment (in theory) to cement it in your long-term memory. There’s debate on how well these things work; I confess I’ve never tried them myself, but I’ve spoken to a few folks who used them to learn a new language and swore them helped. YMMV.)</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-10">
            <br>
                <hr class="hr5">
            <br>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">So, yeah: Use it or lose it. If you want to learn programming, try to squeeze in a few minutes to do it every day. The same goes for any other skill acquisition.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">You probably already knew this rule!</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">But now you know <em>why.</em></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
